Review: Would’ve given 5 stars if it weren’t for the people clapping in the theater after every song

Fascinating dialogue. I feel that I need to rewatch this to develop a true understanding and opinion, but I’m left feeling exhausted, fed, and riddled with uncertainties about our world and the way I conduct my life. Who the hell am I and why am I here. So many late journeys home through the darkened city streets have felt just like Wallace Shawn’s at the end of this film.
Why does rami malek have to ruin every moment of cinema he appears in with his overactive beady eyes and pursed lips. You’re doing way too much, Rami, it’s just a cameo.
Funny, visually exciting, necessarily meta and well done to that end. Still there’s no getting around the fact that this is a 2 hour ad for a toy, no matter how clever and feel good it is.
Makes me wanna get a dozen of my closest guy friends together and do tai chi in the arid Djibouti landscape
Inventive, exciting, funny, and occasionally overstimulating

Great performances all around, a dark and engaging look, and a sometimes clunky plot. It ends a little to cleanly for me, which seems to be a common symptom of mid-2000s screenwriting. One of the most annoying tropes of this period is the overcommitted professional divorcee dad protagonist with a precocious kid son who offers little to the story. We get it: the protagonist is too *complicated* to maintain a marriage, and his loving relationship to his son gives him…
